Maven Web project
Step 1: Open Eclipse
   ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ 1.1 Launch Eclipse IDE.
   ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ 1.2 Select or create a workspace.
Step 2: Create a New Maven Project
   ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ 2.1. File -> New -> Project...
       ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ 2.1.1. Expand "Maven"
       ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ 2.1.2. Select "Maven Project" and click "Next"
Step 3: Choose Maven Archetype
   ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ 3.1. Select an archetype(e.g "'org.apache.maven.archetypes' -> 'maven-archetype-webapp' 1.4 ")
   ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ 3.2. Click "Next"
Step 4: Configure the Maven Project
   ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ 4.1 Group Id: Enter a group ID (e.g., com.example).
   ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ 4.2 Artifact Id: Enter an artifact ID (e.g., my-web-app).
   ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ 4.3 Click **Finish** to create the project.
Step 5: Add Maven Dependencies
   ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ 5.1 Open the **pom.xml** file in the Maven project.
   ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ 5.2 Add the necessary dependencies for your web project (e.g., Servlet, JSP):
Go to browser -> Open mvnrepository.com
 Search for 'Java Servlet API' -> Select the latest version.
 Copy the dependency code -> Paste it in MavenWeb‚Äôs pom.xml under the target folder
       ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ Example:
           ```xml
           <dependency>
               <groupId>javax.servlet</groupId>
               <artifactId>javax.servlet-api</artifactId>
               <version>4.0.1</version>
               <scope>provided</scope>
           </dependency>
           ```
   Step 6:-. Configure server:
    ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ Window -> Show View -> Servers
    ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ Add server -> Select Tomcat v9.0 server -> Click Next
    ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ Configure server options (e.g., ports, server location).
Step 7:-. Modify 'tomcat-users.xml':
    ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ Add role and user details under <tomcat-users> tag.
Step 8:. Build the project:
    ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ Right-click on index.jsp -> Run As -> Maven Clean
    ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ Right-click on index.jsp -> Run As -> Maven Install
    ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ Right-click on index.jsp -> Run As -> Maven Test
    ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ Right-click on index.jsp -> Run As -> Maven Build
Step 9. In the Maven Build dialog:
    ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ Enter Goals: clean install test
    ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ Click on Apply -> Click on Run
Step 10. Check console for BUILD SUCCESS message.
Step 11. Run the application:
    ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ Right-click on index.jsp -> Run As -> Run on Server
    ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ Select the Tomcat server -> Click on Finish



Docker + Redis Complete Steps
Pull Redis Image
docker pull redis

Run Redis Container
docker run --name my-redis -d redi

Check Running Container
docker ps

Access Redis CLI
docker exec -it my-redis redis-cli

Example Redis Commands:
SET name "Alice"
GET name
exit

Stop Container
docker stop my-redis

Start Container
docker start my-redis

Remove Container
docker rm my-redis

Remove Redis Image
docker rmi redis

Working With Dockerfile

Step 1: Create Project Folder

Windows:
cd /c/DockerProjects/Redis

Mac/Linux:
mkdir ~/DockerProjects/Redis
cd ~/DockerProjects/Redis

Step 2: Create Dockerfile with this content:
FROM redis:latest
CMD ["redis-server"]

Docker Commands Step-by-Step

Build Image
docker build -t redisnew .

Run Container
docker run --name myredisnew -d redisnew

Show Running Containers
docker ps

Stop Container
docker stop myredisnew

Login to Docker Hub
docker login

Show All Containers
docker ps -a

Commit Container to New Image
docker commit 0e993d2009a1 budarajumadhurika/redis1

Show Images
docker images

Push Image to Docker Hub
docker push budarajumadhurika/redis1

Remove Container
docker rm 0e993d2009a1

Remove Image
docker rmi budarajumadhurika/redis1

Show Containers Again
docker ps -a

Logout of Docker Hub
docker logout

Pull Image from Docker Hub
docker pull budarajumadhurika/redis1

Run Container from Pulled Image
docker run --name myredis -d budarajumadhurika/redis1

Enter Redis CLI
docker exec -it myredis redis-cli

Set Key
SET name "Abcdef"

Get Key
GET name

Exit Redis CLI
exit

Show Containers
docker ps -a

Stop Container
docker stop myredis

Remove Container
docker rm 50a6e4a9c326

Show Images
docker images

Remove Image
docker rmi budarajumadhurika/redis1

Optional:
docker logout


‚úÖ STEP 1 ‚Äî Create your lab folder
Open terminal and run
Windows:
mkdir C:\compose-lab
cd C:\compose-lab
Mac/Linux:
mkdir ~/compose-lab
cd ~/compose-lab
==================================================
‚úÖ STEP 2 ‚Äî Create docker-compose.yml
Inside compose-lab folder ‚Üí create a file:
docker-compose.yml
PASTE THIS EXACT CONTENT:
version: "3.9"
services:
  web:
    image: nginx:latest
    ports:
      - "8080:80"
  db:
    image: postgres:15
    environment:
      POSTGRES_USER: demo
      POSTGRES_PASSWORD: demo
      POSTGRES_DB: demo_db
üëâ You do NOT modify anything here yet.
==================================================
‚úÖ STEP 3 ‚Äî Run the compose file
Run:
docker compose up -d
Go to browser:
http://localhost:8080
You should see Nginx welcome page.
==================================================
‚úÖ STEP 4 ‚Äî MODIFY docker-compose.yml to Add Redis
Now open docker-compose.yml again.
üëâ You must ADD THIS BLOCK at the bottom under db:
  redis:
    image: redis:alpine
üëâ Then MODIFY the web service to include depends_on.
Change FROM:
web:
  image: nginx:latest
  ports:
    - "8080:80"
CHANGE TO THIS:
web:
  image: nginx:latest
  ports:
    - "8080:80"
  depends_on:
    - redis

‚ö†Ô∏è You are making TWO modifications:
Add redis service
Add depends_on to web
==================================================
‚úÖ STEP 5 ‚Äî Restart Compose
docker compose up -d
docker compose ps
You must see:
web
db
redis
ALL running.
==================================================
‚úÖ STEP 6 ‚Äî Test on another machine
Zip your compose-lab folder
Copy to another system
Run:
docker compose up -d
Same result must appear.
==================================================
‚úÖ STEP 7 ‚Äî MODIFY docker-compose.yml to add network + volume
Now open docker-compose.yml AGAIN.
You must add:
1Ô∏è‚É£ Add networks + volumes at the TOP-BOTTOM (below version)
PASTE THIS BEFORE services or after (either ok):
networks:
  app-net:
volumes:
  db-data:
2Ô∏è‚É£ Modify web service to include networks + depends_on (already there)
Change your web service to this FULL BLOCK:
web:
  image: nginx:latest
  ports:
    - "8080:80"
  networks:
    - app-net
  depends_on:
    - db
3Ô∏è‚É£ Modify db service to include volumes + networks
Change your db service to this full block:
db:
  image: postgres:15
  environment:
    POSTGRES_USER: demo
    POSTGRES_PASSWORD: demo
    POSTGRES_DB: demo_db
  volumes:
    - db-data:/var/lib/postgresql/data
  networks:
    - app-net
üëâ You are modifying BOTH services.

==================================================
‚úÖ STEP 8 ‚Äî Run the updated file
docker compose up -d
Stop:
docker compose down
Start again:
docker compose up -d
üëâ Your database data stays saved.
==================================================
‚úÖ STEP 9 ‚Äî Add Flask app (Development iteration)
Create a file named: app.py
PASTE THIS:
from flask import Flask
app = Flask(__name__)
@app.route("/")
def home():
    return "Hello from Flask + Docker!"
if __name__ == "__main__":
    app.run(host="0.0.0.0", port=5000)
Create a file named: Dockerfile
PASTE THIS:
FROM python:3.10-slim
WORKDIR /app
COPY app.py /app/
RUN pip install flask
CMD ["python", "app.py"]
==================================================
‚úÖ STEP 10 ‚Äî Modify docker-compose.yml AGAIN
Modify ONLY the web service to this:
web:
  build: .
  ports:
    - "5000:5000"
  depends_on:
    - db
==================================================
‚úÖ STEP 11 ‚Äî Build & run
docker compose up --build
Visit:
http://localhost:5000
==================================================
‚úÖ STEP 12 ‚Äî Change app.py and rebuild
Change the line:
return "Hello from Flask + Docker!"
to
return "Hello Docker Compose!"
Rebuild:
docker compose up --build
Browser shows updated text.


